''See also'' '''[[Anno Domini]]'''

==English==
===Etymology===
*Latin ''annō Domini'', from ''[[anno|annō]]'', the [[ablative]] of ''[[annus]]'' (''[[year]])'' + ''[[Domini]]'', the [[genitive]] of '''[[Dominus]]''' (''the [[Lord]]'').

===Alternative spellings===
* '''[[Anno Domini]]'''

===Adverb===
'''anno Domini'''<BR>
'''annō Domini'''

#{{time}} In the year of our Lord, often abbreviated [[AD|A.D.]] or [[AD]]. The religion-neutral [[CE]] for [[Common Era]] is an alternative.

====Usage notes====
* The [[w:Chicago Manual of Style|Chicago Manual of Style]] as well as most house styles require placing the [[A.D.]] before the date (e.g., AD 250), although in casual use it is frequently found following the date.

====Synonyms====
* (''in the year of our Lord''): [[AD]], [[AD|A.D.]], [[CE]], [[Common Era]], [[in the year of our Lord]]

====Antonyms====
* (''in the year of our Lord''): [[BC]], [[BC|B.C.]], [[BCE]], [[Before Christ]]

====Translations====
''See'' [[Anno Domini]]

===See also===
*[[CE]]
*[[w:Wikipedia talk:Manual of Style (dates and numbers)/archive9|Wikipedia discussion of style]]


